			&nbsp;<a href="JavaScript:openWindow('pop_mail.asp?id=6024')"><img src="icon_email.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Email Poster" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&amp;REPLY_ID=40993&amp;TOPIC_ID=5117&amp;FORUM_ID=2&amp;CAT_ID=1&amp;Forum_Title=General+Discussions&amp;Topic_Title=Guild+Problem%2C+please+help&amp;M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="2" color="#545A7D">
        
         The main problem here is if you apply a rule of considering multiplayers as one players, you have no way of enforcing the rule fairly.  You may identify one or more of these people, but not others - leaving you applying a double standard and with lots of upset people.</P><P>I'd say this situation has to be looked at with the same discression you would with any loot distribution.  If someone appears to be abusing their privilages to being on the raid (ie. bringing extra characters and then only playing one), then you have recourse to bite down and deny them additional merits/rolls.  However, if they contribute and play nice with everyone in working towards your goal, they deserve consideration as anyone else for each character in my book.  In any event, it's the raid leader's discression.  Loot is a privilage and I've never looked kindly on people who consider it a 'right.'  It's your raid, you make the rules.  If folks don't like it, there's plenty other activities available to take up their time.  Like taking the next TL out of town for instance...</P><P></P><P><BR>Takilth Shadowpath<BR>Iksar Warlock of the Final Shedding<BR>proud member of Shining Alliance<BR>Prexus<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
      </tr>

