        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&amp;REPLY_ID=41045&amp;TOPIC_ID=5117&amp;FORUM_ID=2&amp;CAT_ID=1&amp;Forum_Title=General+Discussions&amp;Topic_Title=Guild+Problem%2C+please+help&amp;M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="2" color="#545A7D">
        
         Xzzy was right on the mark when he mentioned there being two kinds of raids.  There are guild raids and open raids.  In guild situations everyone knows each other fairly well (or should) and it's more feasable to apply a "main" vs "secondary" character rule.  However in open raids, there is no way to always know who is a main and who is a secondary character, who is being multiplayed, or who is being played by a friend.  The open raid is the situation where discression of the raid leader is most critical, and the one where you have to turn a blind eye to who's behind the keyboard.  In those situations, if the character contributes, they should probably merit inclusion on consideration.  In guild raids you have the luxury of leaning things more towards "what's best for the guild" and maximizing distribution more fairly towards the players vs the characters.</P><P></P><P>Takilth Shadowpath<BR>Iksar Warlock of the Final Shedding<BR>proud member of Shining Alliance<BR>Prexus</P><P>Edited by - Takilth SP on 06/17/2002  14:05:59<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
